	   <tr><td colspan=2>You don't mention your level but I assume you are referring to the level 12 charm spell, which puts you somewhere around level 12-15.<br><br>As far as an average duration it's really hard to say.&nbsp;&nbsp;Personally, I didn't really start charm soloing until somewhere in the 30s when we get some longer duration (and slightly more reliable .... ???) charms.<br><br>The max duration on the spell is 8 minutes which could give you time to mow through more than a couple MOBs if you cast Languid Pace on the ones you are pulling.  Unfortunately you don't get a haste spell, which really makes charm soloing effective, until 16.<br><br>This is how I have heard that it works when determining if a MOB will break a charm spell.  There is a chance they will break it every tick (6seconds) and they get three rolls to possibly break it.  The first roll is affected by your level vs. that of the MOB.  The second roll is affected by the magic resist of the MOB, which is good reason to always cast tash before charming for maximum results.  The third roll is affected by your charisma.<br><br>As far as whether it will be reliable or not I would say with your twinked charisma it's worth a shot.  Even if it turns out to be a bomb it'll be good learning experience for charm soloing in the future.<br><br>Some pointers before you set out.  First of all, make sure that you have SoW potions or some reliable way of getting a regular sow when you need it.  If charm breaks and you don't have sow you won't last long with 2 angry MOBs beating on you.<br><br>I also recommend charming in spacious outdoor zones where adds are not likely since it can take some room to get things under control when it gets messy.<br><br>Keep a mezz and a root spell memmed also for keeping things under control.  And make sure you do at least 1 point of damage to the MOB you are killing, otherwise your pet steals 50% of the experience for the kill.  This can easily be done by casting your lowest level nuke on the MOB during the fight.<br><br>Lastly, charm soloing can be a lot of things.  It's great xp, arguably the best solo xp in the game since you can chain pull high blues when things are going well.  When things are going very well you can actually gain mana while gaining very good xp.  When things don't go well, it can be very frustrating, mana intensive, and possibly dangerous.  Try not to get hit at all, and make sure that sow is kept up.  It can be tons of fun also.  The edge-of-your-seat rush of having no idea when all hell will break loose keeps you on your toes to say the least.  Some of my best in-game moments have been charm soloing.<br><br>Feel free to ask any other questions and hopefully this helped you out some.<br><br>-Yizz<br>&nbsp;<br> </td></tr>
