<table  border=0 cellpadding=2 cellspacing=0 awidth=100%><a name=103535308998011></a><form action=http://eqdb.allakhazam.com/strategy/mrate.pl name=f103535308998011><tr><td id=headerrow><a id=sj href=classes.html?class=13&mid=103535308998011>RE: Making Jewrly</a> <a id=fs8 href=classes.html?class=13&mid=103535308998011#post><img src=http://everquest.allakhazam.com/static/reply.gif border=0 alt="Reply..." height=16 width=16></a></td><td align=right id=headerrow valign=bottom><span id=notbold>By:</span> <a href=poster.html?user=43653><span id=Scholar>GLASS</span></a>, <span id=Scholar>Scholar</span><br><span id=notbold>172 posts</td></tr>
	   <tr><td colspan=1 id=headerrow>Posted @ Wed, Oct 23rd 2:23 AM 2002</td>
	   <td id=headerrow align=right><span id=notbold>Score</span>: Decent<span id=notbold>[3.44]</span></td></tr>
	   <tr><td colspan=2>I agree with Dargadin, you should max out the number of practice points you can spend on jewelcraft at the outset.&nbsp;&nbsp;Is it 21 or 19 though?  Either way, max it out and work from there.<br><br>Having said that, I would recommend that you put off getting serious about jewelcraft until the much higher levels.  Here's why.<br><br>Your success rate and chances of improving are based on your Intelligence.  As a lower level player, you most likely don't have the greatest INT gear available.  But, you will improve that gear as you level up.  Not only that, but you will start getting spells that you can use to temporarily boost your intelligence even further.  The higher your INT the easier (and less-costly) jewelry will be.<br><br>Also, since it is such an expensive tradeskill, you won't want to be spending all of your hard-earned plat suffering through practice sessions while still wearing raw silk &quot;armor&quot;.  Spend your money in earlier levels getting better equipment so that you can be a more effective enchanter.  Once you have arrived, so to speak, the plat will be easier to come by and your intelligence will be much higher.<br><br>Another thing, ALWAYS enchant your bars before attempting a combine.  An enchanted piece, as Dargadin also hit on, will actually sell back to the vendors for more than the cost of materials.  If it's not enchanted, you'll get far less.<br><br>One last pointer, you will notice that when moving through the trivial charts, that it will become seemingly cheaper at some point to move from combining the less-costly metal with the next gem than to move up to the more costly metal and combine with a less-costly gem.  Don't fall for it.  Move through every gem possible with one metal until each becomes trivial.  Your success rate will be MUCH higher which means that you will get more back from the merchants from selling the made items.  Does that make sense?  Let me know if not and I'll try to explain it again.<br><br>Have fun.<br><br>-Yizz<br>&nbsp;<br> </td></tr>
